The study of researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common and soprano pipistrelles and also brown long-eared and daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in important locations around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS employees and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
Expert audio analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of bat conversations and what species do what.
A habitat map and report will then be produced to create a detailed landscape-scale picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, natural science advisor to NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat, natural homes, which are most important to the bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the acquisition of meadows and how it is best to maintain equal forest areas for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the United Kingdom have decreased significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects rest areas and loss of habitat/residential sites.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, such as flypaper and some chemical treatments of building materials, and also attacks of pet cats.
Bats are not actually blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are still more useful than their eyes in catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to find errors and obstacles in their flight.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes the bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, rest inspections, and sometimes save lives.
The organization has even created Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve on the Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Property manager David Thompson says the property is the ideal territory for them.
"Here at Threave we have a great area for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, many veteran trees and all the good habitats.
But there is a lot about bats that are still unknown, so the work we do here and on other properties will help us understand more about what they need to thrive."
He underscores the importance of checking for bats before performing maintenance within real estate, since it is possible that the infinite destruction of a single habitat can kill up to 400 women's bats and young people, and perhaps eradicate an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them or destroy their resting places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to come in and help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we don't know how their populations are dangerous."
