Update on dinoflagellates: Concentration is reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission (FWC) shows a general reduction in the concentration of dinoflagellates in the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, uneven conditions for growth are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and the counties around Collier - suggesting reduction in concentration.
A growth of dinoflagellates spreads over approximately 200 km on the coastline from northern Pinellas to the southern counties of Lee.
Areas with dinoflagellates are found about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough, but compared to last week there are fewer areas.
Dinoflagellates have and have been observed in Pasco.
Medium-sized concentration has been reported in Pinellas over the past week, low to high concentration along the coast in Hillsborough, low concentration in Manatee, high concentration along the coast in Sarasota, medium-sized concentration in Charlotte, high concentration in Lee, and low concentration in Collier.
Irritation in the airways is still reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier.
Irritation in the airways was not reported northwest of Florida in the last week.
